		<category><![CDATA[Fibromyalgia and back pain]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[pool therapy]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://healthmattershow.com/?p=27482</guid>
		<description>Fibromyalgia and back pain is a timely topic. Learn more about conquering back pain and overcoming Fibromyalgia with pool therapy on the Health Matters Show.</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class="tweetmeme_button" style="float: left; margin-right: 10px;">
			<a href="http://api.tweetmeme.com/share?url=http%3A%2F%2Fhealthmattershow.com%2Ffibromyalgia-and-back-pain%2F"><br />
				<img src="http://api.tweetmeme.com/imagebutton.gif?url=http%3A%2F%2Fhealthmattershow.com%2Ffibromyalgia-and-back-pain%2F&amp;style=normal&amp;b=2" height="61" width="50" /><br />
			</a>
		</div>
<p><a href="http://healthmattershow.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/Cinda-Crawford-best-media-pic.jpg"><img src="http://healthmattershow.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/Cinda-Crawford-best-media-pic-239x300.jpg" alt="" title="Cinda Crawford" width="239" height="300" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-20109" /></a>Some time ago, I healed from the worst, primary symptoms of <strong>Fibromyalgia</strong>, but not the <strong>back pain</strong>. That&#8217;s probably because of several reasons, not the least of which is that Fibromyalgia and back pain go together like Jello and Cool Whip. Think Bill Cosby.</p>
<p>It can be difficult for even the most seasoned professional physician to tell when back pain stems from a dysfunction of the back or is simply another symptom of Fibro. That&#8217;s because pain all along the back is a classic part of the illness.</p>
<p>I wrote the following article about the two conditions for another publication and now I want to share it with you. So very many people suffer with Fibromyalgia and back pain everyday. Feel free to leave a comment and share your experiences with others. </p>
<p><center><i>Pain is pain, but it can arrive with a thousand daggers.</i></center></p>
<p>Thank you so much,<br />
Cinda Crawford, your host of the <strong>Health Matters Show</strong></p>
<p><center></p>
<h1>Conquering Back Pain</h1>
<p></center><br />
<!-- AudioAcrobat.com Player code BEGIN -->
<div class="aaplayer"><iframe src="https://www.audioacrobat.com/playweb?audioid=Pdcba17cafe80578a63b4345b66ff071fZVl7RnxuY2B8Uw&amp;buffer=5&amp;shape=6&amp;fc=33CCCC&amp;pc=CCFFFF&amp;kc=20&amp;bc=FFFFCC&amp;brand=1&amp;player=ap21" height="20" width="246" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"></iframe><br />
  <br/><a rel="enclosure" href="http://www.audioacrobat.com/export/Pdcba17cafe80578a63b4345b66ff071fZVl7RnxuY2B8Uw.mp3">   <img src="http://www.audioacrobat.com/images/buttons/downloadmp3.gif" width="72" height="16" border="0" alt="MP3 File"/></a></div>
<p><!-- AudioAcrobat.com Player code END -->(Audio podcast is 6 minutes 1 second)<br />
<span id="more-27482"></span><br />
A few years ago, while in the process of mending and healing from earlier, long-term illnesses (one of them Fibromyalgia), I found myself in considerable back pain. I incorrectly had assumed I would be totally free of all pain soon, but no&#8230;my back continued to hurt! Why? Did I have something else wrong?</p>
<p>Granted some activities produced more symptoms than others. Walking, running, standing and bending were the biggest culprits capable of inducing cramping, spasms, tight muscles and a pain level that could take me to my knees. On my worst ten-out-of-ten pain level days, I stayed in bed to avoid taking multiple, strong, prescription drugs.</p>
<p>When walking became necessary, the exertion of trudging through a super-sized store would be the most challenging activity of all. One particular store’s long aisles offered few places to rest, forcing me to walk with a cane, rest, walk some more, stop again, then more walking…finally leaning on my cane for all it was worth or grabbing onto a store fixture sturdy enough to support me. Surely, an inadequate and ineffective way to get where I wanted to go. </p>
<p>Finally, in exhaustion, a stratospheric level of pain stopped me cold and headed me towards the limits of tolerance and brain delirium. Was it possible to get my errand done or did I need to leave the store before someone called 911? Luckily, no experience ever went quite that far, but I came terrifyingly close to such humiliation several times. It truly was no fun to get in that much pain and have so few options. </p>
<p>One day I walked halfway through a store. My back seized up in aisle five, leaving me in excruciating pain. I stood hobbled over, sweaty and in tears. Suddenly, a store clerk stood before me with a puzzled look. She didn’t know what to do&#8211; offer me help, call her manager or what.</p>
<p>Another day, in another situation, the quizzical party eyeing me was a drugstore pharmacist. “May I help you, ma’am? Do you need a chair or some other help? I’m happy to call someone for you.”</p>
<p>“No, thank you, sir. I need pain relief. Do you have anything to help my aching back?”</p>
<p>His answer was one I had heard before: apply a heating pad or muscle rub ointment or take an over-the-counter pain reliever. Truthfully, even today there are not adequate answers other than taking strong pain medications prescribed by a doctor. That day, if I had had a script for a pain drug, the pharmacist could have filled it and technically helped me, but I’m not inclined to live my life with that single, limited choice. No, I wanted more of an answer than…take a pill.</p>
<p>The life-altering pain lingered. The problem threatened to compromise my happy return to good health that I had envisioned. The constant agony worked on me emotionally, from the inside out. In my down moments, I envisioned an ugly world. Housebound. An invalid. Stuck, and laying on my back in a squalid bed, away from people, away from the world which I wanted to frolic in again so badly. </p>
<p>Suddenly, my future sprang forth in truth like my young being born: unless I did something major, my back pain neither would go away nor get better.</p>
<p>That’s when I booked an appointment with my general practice doctor. An x-ray revealed two bulging spinal discs. Weak back and stomach muscles plus my history of living for many years as a semi-invalid made me that much more likely a candidate for back pain. My physician recommended physical therapy and the option that sounded the most doable and pleasant to me: warm-water <b>pool therapy</b>. </p>
<p>Very soon I scheduled physical therapy sessions with a business in town that had its own warm water pool facility and offered this specialized therapy. I suspected that the process of getting stronger and exercising might proceed slowly. The words arduous and torturous come to mind even now as I remember those first few weeks. The reality was that I did not have a robust level of energy; I had to push myself. </p>
<p>The therapist started me slowly, but soon she had me walking laps in the pool and pushing and pulling my legs against the resistance of the water. Next came stretches, squats and leg lift repetitions for muscle building. All of the exercises strengthened my major back muscles in addition to improving my overall conditioning. I moved better, gained muscle mass and felt more flexible. It wasn’t long before every aspect of the warm water therapy program was working together for my good!</p>
<p>To get some variety in my training program, I independently signed up for entry-level water aerobics classes at the local gym. The water was waist-high and I moved about with ease. I did not worry about keeping my balance and noticed improvements in what I could do there, too.</p>
<p>When I took Deep Water classes, my feet didn’t touch the bottom of the pool. That’s when I donned a ski belt to keep me afloat. If I had struggled to keep my head above water, I surely would have expended too much energy and not done well in the class as far as building my back and overall muscles.</p>
<p>No, staying buoyant with the security of the ski belt allowed me to feel free, joyous and a little like a kid rocking and rolling in the water. My time in the pool turned out to be some of the most fun I had enjoyed in a long time. I gained agility and ability, plus had fun doing it.</p>
<p>Occasionally I used other water exercise tools to work out, too, such as webbed gloves for pushing and pulling me forward, foam-like dumb bells for lifting <em>weights</em> under the water, stretch bands for doing resistance exercises and, finally, specially-designed shoes made to create more resistance as I walked. Those built up leg, calf and ankle muscles. In doing the whole routine, I found that anything I did to strengthen my torso also helped my back. </p>
<p>But the improvement benefits were implied, not guaranteed. It was my responsibility to do my exercises right and not hurt myself. If I acted frivolously and did some movement wrong, I risked personal injury. </p>
<p>As I look back today, I know that my effort and time spent in doing warm water pool therapy meant I could avoid most, strong pain medications and, maybe, an invasive back surgery or two. So far, so good. This approach worked on a grand scale for me. Will it work for everyone? Probably not.</p>
<p>However, if you’re someone who would rather take charge of your health and aren’t afraid to try something new, maybe it could help you. Personally, I’m glad I didn’t leave my medical fate to chance. Physical therapy truly helped me. That’s why I feel truly grateful to my doctor for recommending this particular health-promoting answer.</p>
<p>Do I have even more, new and exciting health horizons ahead of me? I&#8217;m betting I do. After all, I&#8217;m ahead so far in conquering Fibromyalgia and back pain!</p>
