		<item>
		<title>Diagnosis of Fibromyalgia: Why is it so tough to get an accurate diagnosis?</title>
		<link>http://healthmattershow.com/diagnosis-of-fibromyalgia-why-is-it-so-tough-to-get-an-accurate-diagnosis/</link>
		<comments>http://healthmattershow.com/diagnosis-of-fibromyalgia-why-is-it-so-tough-to-get-an-accurate-diagnosis/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 25 May 2012 14:15:06 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>cinda@getwellhealth.com (Cinda Crawford)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Health Matters Shows]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[diagnosis of Fibromyalgia]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://healthmattershow.com/?p=27454</guid>
		<description>Learn why it is so tough to get an accurate diagnosis of Fibromyalgia at the Health Matters Show with Cinda Crawford, your host.</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class="tweetmeme_button" style="float: left; margin-right: 10px;">
			<a href="http://api.tweetmeme.com/share?url=http%3A%2F%2Fhealthmattershow.com%2Fdiagnosis-of-fibromyalgia-why-is-it-so-tough-to-get-an-accurate-diagnosis%2F"><br />
				<img src="http://api.tweetmeme.com/imagebutton.gif?url=http%3A%2F%2Fhealthmattershow.com%2Fdiagnosis-of-fibromyalgia-why-is-it-so-tough-to-get-an-accurate-diagnosis%2F&amp;style=normal&amp;b=2" height="61" width="50" /><br />
			</a>
		</div>
<p><a href="http://healthmattershow.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/check-mark.jpg"><img src="http://healthmattershow.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/check-mark.jpg" alt="" title="check mark" width="144" height="147" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-27461" /></a>If you’ve experienced trouble in getting a <b>diagnosis of Fibromyalgia</b> (FM), you’re not alone. Many people want to know why is it so tough to get an accurate diagnosis. Today, let’s look at 3 reasons why this may be happening and then catch the 3 bonus points below. You want to get this right!</p>
<p>1) Not all medical professionals can easily diagnose Fibromyalgia.</p>
<p>The truth be told, this illness should not be that confusing, but it often is. The specific diagnosis criteria is out there and available to any medical professional. Either you have the symptoms or you don&#8217;t!<br />
<!-- AudioAcrobat.com Player code BEGIN -->
<div class="aaplayer"><iframe src="https://www.audioacrobat.com/playweb?audioid=P5caf35a57cdeeb63cec054bdc29d659cZVl7RnxuY2B9Wg&amp;buffer=5&amp;shape=6&amp;fc=33CCCC&amp;pc=CCFFFF&amp;kc=20&amp;bc=FFFFCC&amp;brand=1&amp;player=ap21" height="20" width="246" frameborder="0" scrolling="no"></iframe><br/><a rel="enclosure" href="http://www.audioacrobat.com/export/P5caf35a57cdeeb63cec054bdc29d659cZVl7RnxuY2B9Wg.mp3"><img src="http://www.audioacrobat.com/images/buttons/downloadmp3.gif" width="72" height="16" border="0" alt="MP3 File"/></a></div>
<p><!-- AudioAcrobat.com Player code END --><br />
(Audio podcast is 8 minutes 59 seconds)<br />
<span id="more-27454"></span><br />
After taking a careful medical history and doing a thorough exam, a doctor should be able to make a diagnosis for or against Fibromyalgia.</p>
<blockquote><p>In the hustle and bustle of obtaining a diagnosis of Fibromyalgia, it is sometimes easy to assume erroneous suppositions and a definitive diagnosis becomes a pipe dream effectively lost in an array of blood tests, x-rays, etc. If this happens to you, keep bringing your physician back to center so that you have a better chance of getting the diagnosis of Fibromyalgia, <em>or whatever condition you have</em>. Again, anyone can exhibit multiple symptoms. They can seem like Fibromyalgia, but be something different. However, if you&#8217;re suffering with this chronic pain condition, you have it and you need help in recovering from it. There is no quasi or borderline state of <i>maybe</i> Fibromyalgia once you meet the criteria for diagnosis. </p>
<blockquote><p>The important point here is that it&#8217;s important to keep progressing and moving forward in your recovery process. Get your questions answered. Try to stay on track and obtain a diagnosis. Don&#8217;t get lost in confusion.</p></blockquote>
<p>3) Sadly, this third reason is the most distressing of all. In our world of abundant, easy-to-obtain information, research reports, scientific studies, etc., there remain some doctors who “do not believe in Fibromyalgia&#8221;. I guess they missed both the American Rheumatologist Association’s diagnosis criteria and the Social Security Administrations’ ruling of 99-2p, the latter of which spells out the specific criteria that a person must meet to qualify for disability due to incapacitating Fibromyalgia. There are hundreds and thousands of other documents that prove the illness exists.</p>
<blockquote><p>Find the search box on the Health Matters Show website and put in the term Fibromyalgia. You&#8217;ll get a large volume of data right here!</p></blockquote>
<p>BONUS INFORMATION: The keys to being successful are:</p>
<ul>
<li>Go to your doctor visits prepared,</li>
<li>Certainly investigate all possible, troublesome health conditions, but don’t allow the exercise to hinder you in getting a correct diagnosis of what is bothering you, and </li>
<li>Don’t be dissuaded by one or two nay-sayers. If you suspect that you have the condition and you want a doctor to address what&#8217;s wrong with you, then stay the course.</li>
</ul>
<p>Look for a professional who will take you seriously and give you an accurate diagnosis of Fibromyalgia. They are out there.</p>
<p>Cinda Crawford, host of the Health Matters Show </p>
